<p class="pageheader">Personal Responsibility?  A Response to John Smedley's Blog of October 26, 2006
<div class="pageheaderauthor">By <a href="mailto:kwill@vaultnetwork.com">Kwill</a></div>
<hr noshade/></p>
<b>11-06-2006</b> - 
“I think it’s all the same in the end. We all have to make our own choices. I don’t believe for a second that WoW (or any other MMO including our own) is designed to get people hooked.”  – <a target="_blank" href="http://stationblog.wordpress.com/2006/10/26/personal-responsibility">John Smedley</a>, in response to this <a target="_blank" href="http://soulkerfuffle.blogspot.com/2006/10/view-from-top.html">blog</a> from an ex-World of Warcraft player.<p>

I would like to think that too, I really would.  I would also like to think Las Vegas wasn’t put on this planet to get people hooked on gambling.  The house always wins …. But people don’t want to believe that.    People make choices, but often those choices are nudged by psychological factors that are very hard to ignore.  And when you can play a compellling game that doesn’t even require you to get dressed and leave the house … well, you know the rest.<p>

I think writing this blog response is really naïve on the part of John Smedley, and rather disingenuous.  I think the original blog was well written and gave compelling reasons why MMOs can cause people real problems.   Smed makes some interesting analogies to other games, but there are so many ways that EverQuest and all other MMO’s are more compelling than playing Magic the Gathering cards or Dungeons and Dragons on paper.<p>

First of all, MtG before it was on the internet, at least, required that you have people over and spend physical time with another person.  It may have been something you got hooked on, but it was limiting due to the fact that you can’t really spend 48 hours straight in someone else’s living room, at least in most people’s worlds.  You meet up with a friend or friends, have a few games, and go home.  Same with Dungeons and Dragons.  Fast forward to online computer games, and suddenly it’s quite easy to stay in front of your machine for 24, 36, 48 hours straight … there’s always something to do and someone to group up with.  It’s 24/7 opportunity.  If you fell asleep during a D&D session at the table, people probably told you to go home.  Fall asleep in front of the keyboard, and it’s a different story.  Wake up, drink another Mountain Dew Code Red, and keep going.<p>

But that isn’t necessarily SOE’s problem.  It’s the nature of the gameplay that is.  Creating an enjoyable activity that delivers intermittent reinforcement (loot sometimes, not all the time, and not for everyone) is the most powerful psychological motivator to keep people pressing the button for the cheese.  Just ask any freshman in Psych 101.   Add the factor of interpersonal competition with all the other cheese-grabbers and you can get intermittent reinforcement for just as long as you care to stay in the game and keep killing things.  Competition for scarce rewards equals a very powerful psychological force as well as fun times.  And make no mistake about it, the development team spends 80 hour weeks figuring out how to make the game more fun and entertaining so you stay hooked, for years.  They want you raiding instead of mowing the lawn or shopping at the mall.  And rightly so, that’s their job, to make the game great so you don’t want to do anything else with your time.<p>

It’s also easy to get hooked on being someone else, and live in another world that is essentially perfect 24/7, 365 days a year.  You don’t have to make any effort to do anything that’s remotely civilized when you play other than communicate with other people, and some people don’t even do that too well.  There are no real personal problems in the virtual world that can’t be solved by putting someone on ignore or doing a server transfer, and constant gratification as you move up the levels.  Some people, such as the original blogger, feel very important and powerful in the virtual world.  You are a hero every day.  Who wouldn’t be hooked on that?<p>

And let’s face it.  When you play EverQuest the way it’s meant to be played -- and probably WoW too, but even more so for EQ --  things take an enormous amount of time.  Want to get flagged for Time?  Hours of playtime.  You can’t get Qvic flagged in 20 minutes, either.  You can’t get your Anguish signets in less than a few hours, even if you are organized and very effective and can beat all the encounters in the minimum amount of time.  You can’t even get to most higher level zones without spending 10 minutes travelling around.  This game is “addictive” because it’s time consuming to enjoy the challenging content, and the more you play, the more content you get to experience, and the more you feel compelled to play.  There’s no end to the gameplay, either.  You can’t “win” EverQuest.  So again, how naïve is it for the President of SOE to say that some people are just “obsessed” when the entire thrust of the game is for a person to be online for 4-5 hours, a few days a week? That’s who the designers are designing for, not the person who wants to log on for 30 minutes and log off again.  The immense distances you must travel to get to the encounters, the time it takes to complete them and the teamwork required, as well as the basic concept that to level up takes hours of time is the core of the MMO game today.  Tradeskills? Tremendous timesink, and again, intermittent reinforcement with a promise of success at the end.<p>

I am not saying that’s wrong to play EQ, heaven knows I play enough of it, but I am suggesting that to say that it’s just a game and not a very time consuming hobby is to invalidate Smed’s core group of subscribers!  Sure, it’s fun to play EQ and I have spent thousands of hours of my life doing just that.  But don’t tell me that it’s only my choice to play endlessly, since that’s the way you have designed your game.  To play it means to be involved and obsessed in ways that aren’t possible with most other hobbies, mostly because there are so few physical limitations to becoming hooked – an internet connection and a decent computer and $14.99 a month is all it takes to become an EQ addict.<p>

Personal responsibility says that you don’t let your cat starve or get fired from your job because you are playing an online game.  But when faced with the powerful psychological forces brought to bear by today’s MMO environment, it’s no wonder that many people succumb at least partly to playing way too much.  There must be some corporate responsibility for the providers of an alluring service in recognizing it is a powerful force, as well demanding personal responsibility of people who avail themselves of the service.  So is it the game’s fault the people get “hooked”?  Yes, I think it is, partially because it’s designed that way.  Saying it’s not is also being in denial, Smed.  How else can you keep getting people to log on, day after day, year after year but by providing something that is so fascinating it becomes addictive to some people?   Saying that one has to make a choice, or “take personal responsibility” is admitting that players can make the wrong choice, and that there are consequences to that behavior.  Maybe a more appropriate blog response would be, “yeah, our game is so fun people get addicted to it!”  At least then we could feel good about our obsession.

